  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect in several key ways:\n\n1. International Conventions and Treaties\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- These establish global standards and frameworks for combating money laundering\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries cooperate through formal agreements to investigate and prosecute money laundering\n- Shared information and evidence across jurisdictions\n- Extradition of individuals involved in financial crimes\n\n3. Compliance Requirements\n- Banks and financial institutions must implement international anti-money laundering (AML) standards\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n- Customer due diligence protocols\n\n4. Regulatory Harmonization\n- Countries align their national laws with international standards\n- Similar legal definitions of money laundering\n- Consistent approaches to financial monitoring and investigation\n\n5. Enforcement Mechanisms\n- Coordinated investigations across borders\n- Sanctions for non-compliance\n- International pressure on jurisdictions with weak AML frameworks\n\n6. Information Sharing Platforms\n- Interpol\n- Egmont Group of Financial Intelligence Units\n- Facilitate cross-border intelligence exchange\n\nThese intersections create a complex, multilayered approach to preventing and prosecuting money laundering globally.",
